{
  "doc_id": "21330",
  "text": "The Yes-associated protein (YAP) was originally identified on the basis of its interaction with the Src family kinase Yes [CITATION_1] . YAP functions primarily as a co-transcription factor that interacts with various DNA binding proteins, including the transcription factors RUNX, TEAD/TEF, and p73, to regulate gene expression [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Genetic screens independently identified the Drosophila ortholog Yki as a gene that regulates cell proliferation and apoptosis [CITATION_4] . Both Yki and YAP are regulated by a conserved kinase cascade that includes Hippo (Hpo) and its mammalian orthologs MST1/2, which interact with Salvador (Sav) in flies or SAV1 (also known as WW45) in mammals. This kinase complex phosphorylates Warts (Wts) (LATS1/2 in mammals), which in turn phosphorylates Ser 168 in Yki in flies and Ser 127 in YAP. Yki/YAP phosphorylation tethers these proteins to 14-3-3 and sequesters them in the cytoplasm, inhibiting nuclear translocation and downstream transcriptional programs.",
